UNDIAGNOSED ILLNESS, CAMEL - KENYA: (MARSABIT) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 29 Apr 2020
Source: Nation via AllAfrica [abridged, edited]
https://allafrica.com/stories/202004300070.html


An outbreak of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV), normally referred to as MERS, has been reported in camels in Marsabit County.

Camels in Turbi, Bubisa, Burgabo, Yagara in Forole and Badhahuri have been diagnosed with the viral respiratory illness according to County Livestock and Fisheries Chief Officer Dr. Wario Sori. "Even as the world currently battles with the aftershocks of COVID-19, there is also an outbreak of a disease caused in livestock by a virus of the coronavirus family that has been witnessed in this county," Dr. Sori told the Nation.

He noted that people with exposure to camels are highly susceptible to MERS-CoV, a dangerous respiratory virus. He said the county is collaborating with the Washington State University and CDC [Kenya] to monitor the MERS situation in the county. "We are working with partners to better understand the risks of this virus, including the source, how it spreads, and how to prevent infections," Dr. Sori said.

Preliminary research has recognised the potential for MERS to spread further and cause havoc to more than 80% of the population in the county who rely on livestock as their economic mainstay.

The disease was first reported in Saudi Arabia in 2012. Researchers have found MERS in camels from several countries. Studies have shown that direct contact with camels is a risk factor for human infection with the virus.

The CDC further states that MERS, like other coronaviruses, likely spreads from an infected person's respiratory secretions, such as through coughing [see comment below]. Currently, there is no vaccine available to protect against MERS.

Other livestock disease outbreaks that have been reported in the county include the contagious caprine pleuropneumonia (CCPP) -- also known as goat pneumonia -- in Laisamis Sub-county and goat anaemia (anaplasmosis) in Moyale Sub-county.

So far, all cases of MERS across the globe have been linked to travel to, or residence in, countries in and near the Arabian Peninsula.

[Byline: Jacob Walter]

