[The above media report does not include information supporting its introductory statement, identifying "An outbreak of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) ... in camels in Marsabit County." No information regarding morbidity or human involvement or any other details, clinical or otherwise, indicative of a disease event are included. Until such information becomes available, preferably supported by laboratory investigation, the subject is considered as "undiagnosed."

In addition: Although the statement, attributed to (Kenya's) CDC, according to which "MERS, like other coronaviruses, likely spreads from an infected person's respiratory secretions, such as through coughing" is correct, it should be clear that no cases of "reversed zoonosis" (from human to animal; "anthropozoonosis") have been reported in relation to MERS-CoV. This differs from COVID-19, caused by SARS-CoV-2, for which sporadic cases of human-to-animal (cat and wild felids, minks) transmission of disease have been reported.

As stated in the report, so far, all cases of MERS across the globe have been linked to travel to, or residence in, countries in and near the Arabian Peninsula. A recent article addressed suspected (subclinical) human infections acquired locally in Kenya (Ref 1). Its (abridged) abstract follows:

"The purpose of this study was to determine the presence of antibodies to MERS-CoV in high-risk groups in Kenya. Sera collected from 93 camel handlers, 58 slaughterhouse workers and 35 camel herders were screened for MERS-CoV antibodies using ELISA and PRNT (plaque reduction neutralization test). We found 4 seropositive slaughterhouse workers by PRNT. Risk factors amongst the slaughterhouse workers included being the slaughterman (the person who cuts the throat of the camel) and drinking camel blood. Further research is required to understand the epidemiology of MERS-CoV in Africa in relation to occupational risk, with a need for additional studies on the transmission of MERS-CoV from dromedary camels to humans, seroprevalence and associated risk factors."

Reference
1. Kiyong'a AN, Cook EAJ, Okba NMA, et al. Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) seropositive camel handlers in Kenya. Viruses 2020; 12: 396. https://doi.org/10.3390/v12040396
- Mod.AS

